2. Visualizations using caret

Russ Conte

4/29/2022

The featurePlot function is a wrappter for different lattice plots to visualize the data. For example, the following figures show the default plot for continuous outcomes generated using the featurePlot function.

For classification data sets, the iris data are used for illustration.

Lets create the scatterplot matrix for the iris data set!

transparentTheme(trans = 0.4)
featurePlot(x = iris[,1:4],
            y = iris$Species,
            plot = "pairs",
            ## Add a key at the top to list the names of the irises
            auto.key = list(columns = 3))

Scatterplot Matrix with Ellipses

featurePlot(x = iris[,1:4],
             y = iris$Species,
            plot = "ellipse",
            ## Add a key at the top of the data visualization
            auto.key = list(columns = 3))

# A working example of the same solution using the mpg data set from tidyverse:

mpg1 <- mpg %>% 
  mutate(class = as.factor(class)) # convert y-hat to a factor

featurePlot(x = mpg1[,c(3,8:9)],
            y = mpg1$class,
            plot = "ellipse",
            auto.key = list(7))

Overlayed Density Plots (I like these a lot!)

transparentTheme(trans = 0.9)
featurePlot(x = iris[1:4],
            y = iris$Species,
            plot = "density")


featurePlot(x = iris[,1:4],
            y = iris$Species,
            plot = "density",
            scales = list(x = list(relation = "free"),
                          y = list(relation = "free")),
            adjust = 1.5,
            pch = "|",
            layout = c(4,1),
            auto.key = list(columns = 3))

Repeat similar exercise for density plots using mpg data set from tidyverse:

featurePlot(x = mpg1[,c(3,8:9)],
            y = mpg1$class,
            plot = "density",
            scales = list(x = list(relation = "free"),
                          y = list(relation = "free"),
            adjust = 1.5),
            pch = "|",
            auto.key = list(columns = 3)) # creates three columns for the labels - nice!

Box plots

featurePlot(x = iris[,1:4],
            y = iris$Species,
            plot = "box",
# pass in options to bwplot()
            scales = list(y = list(relation = "free"),
                          x = list(rot = 90)),
            layout = c(4,1),
            auto.key = list(columns = 2))

Repeat similar exercise for box plots using mpg data from tidyverse:

Scatter Plots

For regression, well start with the Boston housing data set:

data("BostonHousing")
regVar <- c("age", "lstat", "tax")
str(BostonHousing[, regVar])
## 'data.frame':    506 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ age  : num  65.2 78.9 61.1 45.8 54.2 58.7 66.6 96.1 100 85.9 ...
##  $ lstat: num  4.98 9.14 4.03 2.94 5.33 ...
##  $ tax  : num  296 242 242 222 222 222 311 311 311 311 ...

When the predictors are continuous, featurePlot can be used to create scatter plots of each of the predictors with the outcome. For example:

theme1 <- trellis.par.get()
theme1$plot.symbol$col = rgb(.2, .2, .2, .4)
theme1$plot.symbol.pch = 16
theme1$plot.line$col = rgb(1,0,0,.7)
theme1$plot.line$lwd <- 2
trellis.par.set(theme1)
featurePlot(x = BostonHousing[,regVar],
            y = BostonHousing$medv,
            plot = "scatter",
            layout = c(3,1))

Note that the x-axis scales are different from one another. The function automaticallyuses scales = list(y = list(relation = "free)) so you dont have to add it. We can also pass in options to the lattice function xyplot. For example, we can add a scatter plot smoother by passing in new options:

featurePlot(x = BostonHousing[, regVar],
            y = BostonHousing$medv,
            plot = "scatter",
            type = c("p","smooth"),
            span = 0.5,
            layout = c(3,1))

Note that the options degree and span control the smoothness of the smoother.

Lets create a feature plot with the continuous variables in the mpg data set. Lets predict and plot highway mileage given the four other continuous values in the data set:

featurePlot(x = mpg1[,c(3:5,8)],
            y = mpg1$hwy,
            plot = "scatter",
            type = c("p", "smooth"),
            span = 0.5,
            layout = c(4,1))
